If the bill passes both houses of Congress, Trump has pledged to veto it and there is little chance Congress could muster the two-thirds necessary to override his veto.
In the likely event the legislature fails to void Trump’s “emergency” declaration, the judicial branch will have the opportunity to check and balance the executive.
No Bona Fide EmergencyThe National Emergencies Act, enacted to limit the president’s authority to declare a national emergency, requires a real emergency.
When he announced in the Rose Garden that he was declaring an “emergency,” Trump admitted there was no real emergency.
By using the pretext of a national emergency to steal money Congress already assigned to other purposes, Trump is circumventing the will of Congress.